<br>
I actually didn't have a personal issue with them raising prices.  Consider that their pricing scheme has been the same since release.  Consider also that there are increased operating costs and heck, even inflation, and they were making far less two months ago from the same customer than they were at the time of release.  In hindsight, a price-hike is pretty damn well inevitable, even to just maintain the status quo.  I don't like having to pay more, but I can understand where they are coming from in raising the prices.<br>
<br>
And while I don't particularly like the increased specs, its something that the needed to do.  Look at pre-SoL graphics compared with the other games out there.  Eye-candy isn't a substantive measure of a game's merits by any means, but you aren't going to attract more folks to play your game, and you won't keep graphics oriented players, if you are using State-Of-The-Art 1998 graphics on a 2002 game.  I would have appreciated having an &quot;Old World&quot; version of the graphics so that those without the specs could perhaps run the zones, but even ignoring the coding nightmare that would be, if the price-hike bothers you as is, consider what it would be if they had spent the resources to implement something like that.<br>
<br>
A lot of the blame that is placed on VI is due to the fact that they were the first to really hit it big in this genre (UO was nice, but it never took off like EQ has).  Everyone after them has had a chance to adapt, to learn from their mistakes, and to code things &quot;right&quot; the first time around, rather than having to deal with repatching existing code and create things from whole cloth.  There's simply no way they could remain competitive without causing at least some degree of inconvienience to their customer base.  Whether or not they have minimized that degree of inconvienience is another thing altogether, and very open to debate, but the fact remains that the old adage about Cake and broken eggs applies.<br>
<br>
As far as system specs for POP... they may not have said whether or not it will bump them, but they have said that it will be using the SoL engine.  Knowing that, I think its pretty safe to rule out another SoL-comparable boost in minimum operating requirements.  It could well be higher than SoLs, but probably not by a large amount, relatively.<br>
<br>
There's a lot of legitimate reasons to be ticked off with VI or Sony about EQ.  Implementing things like the Legends servers rather than increasing overall guide/GM availability, some seemingly idiotic nerf and &quot;rebalancing&quot; decisions, draconian limits on what volunteer guides can do to assist a person, and sloppily implemented (or still non-implemented) zones and features.  Vex Thal, a working Bazaar, visible cloaks, and that &quot;new&quot; GUI they had mentioned all come to mind in specific.  I just don't think being upset about the pricing increase makes a lot of sense.  Suffice to say that I doubt they'd do it if it was unprofitable, and if its profitable, its not offending enough people gravely enough for them to kick their addictions. <p><center>Malevant Faeshadow<br>Speedbump<br> <br> Officer of the Free Company<br><IMG SRC="http://www.unicorntrad.org/three.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/usagemonprayeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sagemon Prayeth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 453<br> <font color=#E9D756>(4/19/02 1:28:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3293.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RANT-EQ: Plane of Power Expansion</span><hr size=1> First of all, let me state the obvious: Sony is in business to make money.  They aren't doing this as a hobby.  They're entitled to charge what the market will bear.  If you want to bitch about prices, ask yourself how much a pair of Nikes costs to make.<br>
<br>
Second, a rational business does not respond to reduced sales by raising its prices.  Make fun of Sony all you want, but we're talking about a very well run company.<br>
<br>
Third, if there has really been such a huge reduction in the subscriber base, why aren't there a bunch of deserted zones?  The zones that are empty today are the same ones that were empty a year ago.<br>
<br>
I'm sure that the subscriber base is down from its peak.  A lot of people have moved on to other games or to real life.  There are new people playing EQ all the time, but the outflow of players has probably been greater than the inflow.  Only Sony would know for sure.  From what I can see, though, EQ looks pretty healthy.<br>
<br>
Even with the increased price, EQ is still pretty cheap entertainment.  If you go to a movie and buy some popcorn and a Coke, you're probably spending as much as you spend on EQ for a month.  You can go to a single NBA game and easily spend more than you spend on EQ for an entire year.<br>
<br>
Of course, that speaks volumes about why attendance is down in the NBA. <p>Sagemon Prayeth<BR>
